WEBVTT

00:02.703 --> 00:04.538
[ Elevator bell dings ]

00:04.572 --> 00:06.274
Very nice meeting you.

00:06.307 --> 00:10.144
**

00:10.178 --> 00:13.747
So, who was that?

00:13.781 --> 00:15.416
A housekeeper.

00:15.449 --> 00:17.385
Leaving your place
at 7:00 in the morning?

00:17.418 --> 00:18.819
I was interviewing her.

00:18.852 --> 00:21.089
You're hiring a housekeeper
for a studio apartment?

00:21.122 --> 00:22.256
I'm not hiring her.

00:22.290 --> 00:23.557
Her clothes don't match.

00:23.591 --> 00:24.825
Right.

00:24.858 --> 00:26.127
Mm.

00:28.862 --> 00:30.631
You're such an asshat,
Shaun Murphy.

00:30.664 --> 00:34.068
**

00:34.102 --> 00:36.570
[ Door opens ]

00:36.604 --> 00:38.839
[ Door closes ]

00:38.872 --> 00:41.509
Today we realize a dream --

00:41.542 --> 00:44.078
seeing our international
humanitarian program

00:44.112 --> 00:45.513
come to fruition.

00:45.546 --> 00:48.716
Our cardiothoracic surgeon,
Dr. Neil Melendez,

00:48.749 --> 00:53.187
in consultation with our head
cardiologist, Dr. Avi Mehta,

00:53.221 --> 00:57.458
evaluated children from Tanzania
to Malawi to Guinea.

00:57.491 --> 00:59.693
They screened
over 100 candidates,

00:59.727 --> 01:01.829
each of them
needing life-saving surgeries.

01:01.862 --> 01:04.632
Ultimately, we decided on a
particularly inspiring young boy

01:04.665 --> 01:06.300
named Gabriel,

01:06.334 --> 01:08.736
who hails from the
Democratic Republic of Congo,

01:08.769 --> 01:10.604
with severe
congenital heart anomalies.

01:10.638 --> 01:13.307
[ Applause ]

01:13.341 --> 01:15.376
We identified
three perfect candidates --

01:15.409 --> 01:16.677
children
I can actually help.
Hi. Thank you.

01:16.710 --> 01:18.712
-Gabriel wasn't one of them.
-Yes and no.

01:18.746 --> 01:20.448
I signed off
on your choices.

01:20.481 --> 01:21.849
But I wouldn't have
necessarily eliminated Gabriel

01:21.882 --> 01:23.451
based on the echo I saw.

01:23.484 --> 01:25.153
A non-surgeon
undermining a surgeon

01:25.186 --> 01:26.820
on his selection
of surgical candidates.

01:26.854 --> 01:28.689
It's healthy
when colleagues challenge

01:28.722 --> 01:29.790
each others' decisions.

01:29.823 --> 01:30.891
It doesn't make any sense.

01:30.924 --> 01:32.160
We gave you
good candidates.

01:32.193 --> 01:33.194
You're not a doctor.

01:33.227 --> 01:35.329
Why wouldn't
you stick with the list?

01:35.363 --> 01:37.898
There were
several intangibles.

01:37.931 --> 01:39.667
**

01:39.700 --> 01:42.470
Can you say hi
to Dr. Melendez?

01:42.503 --> 01:46.274
One of those intangibles,
I'm guessing, is cuteness.

01:46.307 --> 01:48.142
**

01:48.176 --> 01:51.145
-- Captions by VITAC --

01:51.179 --> 01:58.352
**

01:58.386 --> 02:00.321
Family displaced
during the war.

02:00.354 --> 02:01.555
Mother took care
of her husband

02:01.589 --> 02:02.823
until he died
of yellow fever.

02:02.856 --> 02:05.159
He bled out at home.

02:05.193 --> 02:07.161
A month later,
Gabriel was born.

02:10.231 --> 02:11.565
People tend to give more

02:11.599 --> 02:13.901
when the cause is not
only noble, but photogenic,

02:13.934 --> 02:17.205
Adorable kids and sympathetic
moms may work on donors,

02:17.238 --> 02:18.239
but they won't work on me,

02:18.272 --> 02:19.907
and they certainly won't work
on echo results.

02:19.940 --> 02:21.742
Kinda working on me.

02:23.611 --> 02:26.514
Before you say no,
at least do your own work-up.

02:33.387 --> 02:35.623
Winnie:
Mommy, why can't I come?

02:35.656 --> 02:38.526
The hospital's worried
that children bring in germs.

02:38.559 --> 02:40.294
I won't, Mommy.
I promise.

02:40.328 --> 02:42.896
I know, boo.
It's just -- It's the rules.

02:42.930 --> 02:44.765
Okay, baby.
I have to go now.

02:44.798 --> 02:46.900
Do what Aunt Maggie says.
I'll call you later, okay?

02:46.934 --> 02:48.336
I love you to the moon...

02:48.369 --> 02:49.770
And back.

02:49.803 --> 02:50.871
I can't imagine voice rest

02:50.904 --> 02:52.005
could be very easy
with a 3-year-old.

02:52.039 --> 02:55.609
Yeah. Not very effective for
my podcast audience either.

02:55.643 --> 02:57.478
Of which, by the way,
I'm a huge fan.

02:57.511 --> 02:59.780
Grim irony, though, right?

02:59.813 --> 03:01.682
A podcaster
who loses her voice.

03:01.715 --> 03:04.652
Elizabeth, I'm sure
the nodule will be benign

03:04.685 --> 03:05.986
and this'll be nothing more
than an inspiration

03:06.019 --> 03:06.920
for another great episode.

03:06.954 --> 03:09.257
If it's not benign, Isabel?

03:09.290 --> 03:10.524
Let's not get ahead
of ourselves.

03:10.558 --> 03:11.992
Today we're just focused
on removing the nodule

03:12.025 --> 03:12.893
and doing the biopsy.

03:12.926 --> 03:14.462
And you've done
everything you could do.

03:14.495 --> 03:15.629
And when the hoarseness
started,

03:15.663 --> 03:17.265
you sought early care
from the best.

03:17.298 --> 03:18.299
And I sent you to the best.

03:18.332 --> 03:20.668
You work perfectly together,

03:20.701 --> 03:22.536
kind of ping and pong-ish.

03:22.570 --> 03:23.904
[ Both chuckle ]
Claire: It's nice.

03:23.937 --> 03:25.373
A lot of doctors
who are married

03:25.406 --> 03:26.774
are more like
miss and match.

03:26.807 --> 03:28.376
[ Laughs ]

03:28.409 --> 03:31.679
Mrs. Bangura, this is
Dr. Murphy and Dr. Kalu.

03:31.712 --> 03:33.447
They're gonna help me run
some tests on Gabriel.

03:34.715 --> 03:36.284
Jared: I heard
that you and Gabriel

03:36.317 --> 03:37.585
have never been
away from home before.

03:37.618 --> 03:39.287
I was hoping that these
would make him feel welcome.

03:39.320 --> 03:41.455
Georgieta: Yes.
You are kind.

03:42.923 --> 03:46.427
I brought one
for myself, too.

03:46.460 --> 03:48.596
Hey, how 'bout
we all do some medicine?

03:51.365 --> 03:54.768
[ Woman speaking indistinctly
on P.A. ]

03:54.802 --> 04:01.942
**

04:01.975 --> 04:03.744
He really needs our help.

04:03.777 --> 04:10.017
**

04:10.050 --> 04:11.885
"He needs our help"?

04:11.919 --> 04:14.422
He sounds like he's got
a blow dryer in his chest.

04:14.455 --> 04:16.056
Exactly.
Which is why he needs our help.

04:16.089 --> 04:17.625
This is the problem
with cardiologists --

04:17.658 --> 04:18.626
You're really good
at telling people

04:18.659 --> 04:19.693
when something's broken,

04:19.727 --> 04:21.695
not so good at knowing
when they can't be fixed.

04:21.729 --> 04:23.030
If that kid is dying, I'm not
gonna tell his mother that

04:23.063 --> 04:24.598
unless I'm damn sure.

04:24.632 --> 04:25.633
You heard that heart.

04:25.666 --> 04:26.667
I heard that heart.

04:26.700 --> 04:28.436
And it sounded like crap.

04:28.469 --> 04:30.371
But until we do
a transesophageal echo,

04:30.404 --> 04:32.005
I don't know anything.

04:32.039 --> 04:39.780
**

04:39.813 --> 04:41.949
Do a transesophageal echo.

04:41.982 --> 04:44.552
She has a master's degree
in Sociology,

04:44.585 --> 04:46.987
impeccable credentials,
excellent references,

04:47.020 --> 04:49.757
and you turned her away because
"her clothes didn't match"?

04:49.790 --> 04:50.958
It's relevant.

04:50.991 --> 04:54.428
If a life-skills coach can't
select a complementing wardrobe,

04:54.462 --> 04:55.763
they lack life skills.

04:55.796 --> 04:57.731
But she's not gonna pick out
your clothes for you.

04:57.765 --> 04:59.333
She's not a nanny.

04:59.367 --> 05:01.735
She's there to help you
with problem-solving,

05:01.769 --> 05:03.471
financial,
social interactions.

05:03.504 --> 05:05.873
You're doing this
because I did not react well

05:05.906 --> 05:07.708
to a man with a gun
robbing a store I was in.

05:07.741 --> 05:09.843
Statistically,
that is very unlikely

05:09.877 --> 05:11.011
to ever happen
to me again.

05:11.044 --> 05:12.746
Social interactions

05:12.780 --> 05:14.915
will happen again
and again and again.

05:14.948 --> 05:17.117
It's statistically
irrefutable.

05:17.150 --> 05:18.819
And if you learn how
to get along with people

05:18.852 --> 05:20.488
a little bit better,
you'll have a fuller life.

05:20.521 --> 05:22.089
A happier life.

05:22.122 --> 05:24.091
If you don't like this woman,
we'll find somebody else.

05:24.124 --> 05:25.125
I am happy.

05:25.158 --> 05:26.360
You could be happier.

05:26.394 --> 05:27.728
I don't think so.

05:29.096 --> 05:31.365
My neighbor, Lea.

05:31.399 --> 05:34.034
If she were ever in a fire,
she'd be rescued first.

05:34.067 --> 05:35.803
Why's that?

05:35.836 --> 05:38.506
Dr. Melendez says attractive
people have advantages.

05:38.539 --> 05:39.740
[ Laughs ]

05:39.773 --> 05:41.141
Dr. Melendez says that,
does he?

05:41.174 --> 05:42.576
Why is that funny?

05:42.610 --> 05:44.044
I don't know.

05:44.077 --> 05:45.746
It's just, um,
some people

05:45.779 --> 05:48.849
consider Dr. Melendez
attractive.

05:48.882 --> 05:50.751
So, how's it going
with Lea?

05:51.819 --> 05:53.621
She doesn't like me.

05:53.654 --> 05:55.656
Claire:
Why do you say that?

05:55.689 --> 05:59.059
She said I was an asshat.
Yeah?

05:59.092 --> 06:00.894
What was she doing
when she said that?

06:00.928 --> 06:03.964
Touching me.
She was flirting with you.

06:03.997 --> 06:07.535
Sometimes people say
the opposite of what they mean.

06:07.568 --> 06:10.137
Um, they use teasing
as a way

06:10.170 --> 06:11.839
of saying something
they don't mean

06:11.872 --> 06:13.841
instead of saying something
that they do.

06:13.874 --> 06:16.544
I haven't seen any data
on the use of antonyms

06:16.577 --> 06:17.845
as a flirting technique.

06:17.878 --> 06:20.948
Okay. Well, um,
here's what to look for.

06:20.981 --> 06:22.516
You ready?
Yes.

06:22.550 --> 06:24.084
Okay.
The pretentious giggle.

06:24.117 --> 06:25.719
[ Giggles ]

06:25.753 --> 06:28.456
The, uh -- the squirm.

06:28.489 --> 06:30.724
And the hair sweep.

06:30.758 --> 06:32.860
I call it
the flirting trifecta.

06:32.893 --> 06:36.497
Hair scuffing is used in both
animals and humans, Claire.

06:36.530 --> 06:39.099
Secreting glands are located
in the scalp and fur.

06:39.132 --> 06:41.769
Scuffing sends hormones
out into the environment

06:41.802 --> 06:44.772
to let a potential mate
know they're interested.

06:44.805 --> 06:45.906
Or it could be ringworm.

06:45.939 --> 06:48.175
Yeah.

06:48.208 --> 06:50.578
I suppose you have to factor
for that possibility.

06:53.080 --> 06:55.182
Nice touch.

06:55.215 --> 06:56.550
Beauty
increases happiness.

06:56.584 --> 06:57.718
Happiness improves outlook.

06:57.751 --> 06:59.086
Still on Mission Carpe Diem.

06:59.119 --> 07:00.588
You might want to try it.

07:00.621 --> 07:01.789
I'm doing fine.

07:01.822 --> 07:03.090
We're having dinner
at the sink.

07:03.123 --> 07:05.559
No, we're enjoying dinner
at the sink.

07:05.593 --> 07:06.727
Although if you keep
talking like that...

07:06.760 --> 07:08.562
[ Cellphone ringing ]
Mm.

07:10.030 --> 07:12.766
Andrews.

07:12.800 --> 07:15.135
Well, look again.
It has to be there.

07:15.168 --> 07:16.704
Yeah. Okay.

07:18.271 --> 07:19.540
Who was that?

07:19.573 --> 07:20.841
The lab.

07:20.874 --> 07:23.043
They misplaced
Elizabeth's specimen.

07:23.076 --> 07:24.745
Oh, my God.
Don't worry.
They'll find it.

07:24.778 --> 07:27.080
Satisfied?

07:27.114 --> 07:29.149
-It's somewhere.
-Somewhere else.

07:29.182 --> 07:32.252
I love how everyone in surgery
is so fast to blame the lab.

07:32.285 --> 07:33.821
Well, double-checking
can't hurt.

07:33.854 --> 07:34.888
Actually it can.

07:34.922 --> 07:35.823
Because you are here

07:35.856 --> 07:37.725
when you should be
double-checking surgery.

07:37.758 --> 07:39.893
I saw the specimen
go in the container.

07:39.927 --> 07:41.261
It means it has to be here.

07:41.294 --> 07:44.097
No, all that means is that
it was put in a container.

07:44.131 --> 07:45.098
It doesn't mean
that that container

07:45.132 --> 07:47.234
was actually put
in the surgery refrigerator

07:47.267 --> 07:49.269
or that it was actually
picked up by the courier.

07:49.302 --> 07:51.038
He's even worse
than we thought.

07:51.071 --> 07:52.840
Yeah.

07:52.873 --> 07:55.242
Hypertrophic
obstructive cardiomyopathy,

07:55.275 --> 07:57.044
atrial septal defect,

07:57.077 --> 07:59.580
abnormal insertion
of the mitral valve leaflet.

07:59.613 --> 08:02.583
I've never seen so many
anomalies in one heart.

08:05.853 --> 08:08.055
I'm sorry I pushed
for additional testing.

08:08.088 --> 08:11.825
That only got
his mother's hopes up.

08:11.859 --> 08:13.594
Any medication
that'll help?

08:13.627 --> 08:15.563
Beta blockers.

08:15.596 --> 08:16.997
Maybe metoprolol.

08:17.030 --> 08:18.766
It's not like they'll
get him playing soccer,

08:18.799 --> 08:20.868
but they might help him get
to the field to watch.

08:20.901 --> 08:22.970
For a couple of years,
anyway.

08:23.003 --> 08:26.273
Better than dying
on a table tomorrow.

08:26.306 --> 08:28.876
You tell Aoki.

08:30.744 --> 08:32.279
I'll break it to the mom.

08:36.684 --> 08:38.118
[ Rhythmic pounding ]

08:38.151 --> 08:40.153
Woman on P.A.: Dr. Lippman
to plastic surgery.

08:40.187 --> 08:42.623
Dr. Lippman to plastic surgery.

08:42.656 --> 08:44.257
[ Pounding continues ]

08:47.027 --> 08:49.830
[ Pounding continues,
monitor beeping ]

08:49.863 --> 08:52.633
**

08:52.666 --> 08:56.970
It's called sakara,
given by our shaman.

08:59.607 --> 09:01.575
His heartbeat...

09:01.609 --> 09:03.977
it follows the sound.

09:04.011 --> 09:07.881
It reminds it to beat
until you fix it.

09:07.915 --> 09:11.351
Mrs. Bangura,
I've completed all the tests.

09:11.384 --> 09:13.220
And I'm sorry that you've
come all this way --

09:13.253 --> 09:17.691
When Gabriel was in my belly,
evil spirits came to him.

09:17.725 --> 09:19.693
Invade his heart.

09:19.727 --> 09:23.196
Our village shaman
tried to rid them.

09:23.230 --> 09:26.366
He could not.

09:26.399 --> 09:29.903
Then a vision came to him.

09:29.937 --> 09:34.174
A stronger healer
would come.

09:34.207 --> 09:37.344
You.

09:37.377 --> 09:40.313
You will save Gabriel.

09:42.916 --> 09:46.119
I don't know
about evil spirits.

09:46.153 --> 09:48.388
All I know
is that your son was born

09:48.421 --> 09:49.990
with a heart
that I can't fix.

09:50.023 --> 09:51.024
I'm sorry.

09:51.058 --> 09:55.162
I would not have come so far
if I did not believe.

09:59.232 --> 10:02.369
We'll give him medicine
to make him feel better.

10:02.402 --> 10:04.371
And then
you can take him home.

10:04.404 --> 10:14.648
**

10:19.753 --> 10:22.355
[ Woman speaking indistinctly
on P.A. ]

10:26.760 --> 10:28.061
Claire:
We tell her we're sorry,

10:28.095 --> 10:30.063
we have no news yet,
and then --

10:30.097 --> 10:31.832
Nope. You can't say that.
It's an expensive word.

10:31.865 --> 10:34.001
"Sorry"?
You can act sorry.

10:34.034 --> 10:35.202
You can feel sorry.

10:35.235 --> 10:36.737
In fact,
you should feel sorry.

10:36.770 --> 10:37.971
You just can't say it.

10:38.005 --> 10:39.873
Okay, uh,
"I feel bad for you

10:39.907 --> 10:41.875
because we made a mistake
and --"
Nope.

10:41.909 --> 10:43.877
A mistake
isn't a mistake?

10:43.911 --> 10:45.879
Well, it's
"an unanticipated outcome

10:45.913 --> 10:47.380
of an expected action."

10:47.414 --> 10:49.817
You can't use language that
implies blameworthy conduct.

10:49.850 --> 10:52.953
But if we did lose the specimen,
isn't it actually a mistake,

10:52.986 --> 10:55.956
and aren't we sorry,
and aren't we blameworthy?
Yes.

10:55.989 --> 10:59.860
Doesn't mean we can make it
any easier for her attorney.

10:59.893 --> 11:01.729
Hello, Elizabeth.

11:01.762 --> 11:04.064
I'm Jessica Preston
from Risk Management.

11:04.097 --> 11:05.165
How are you?

11:05.198 --> 11:06.199
I don't like
the sound of that.

11:06.233 --> 11:08.869
I know. I really need
a new -- a new job title.

11:08.902 --> 11:11.705
Seems that we've encountered
an unexpected occurrence.

11:11.739 --> 11:13.040
The laboratory
has been unable

11:13.073 --> 11:14.341
to locate
your tissue specimen.

11:14.374 --> 11:17.044
We don't want you to be
unnecessarily alarmed,

11:17.077 --> 11:19.212
but we want you to be fully
aware of what's going on.

11:19.246 --> 11:22.382
But ho-- How will I know
if I have cancer

11:22.415 --> 11:23.717
if you don't find it?

11:23.751 --> 11:25.285
We are looking everywhere.

11:25.318 --> 11:26.286
We will find it.

11:26.319 --> 11:28.722
As long as it's in formalin
or a refrigerator,

11:28.756 --> 11:29.757
everything will be fine.

11:29.790 --> 11:30.557
For how long?

11:30.590 --> 11:33.093
At least 24 hours.
Maybe even 36.

11:35.262 --> 11:36.429
Well,
then you better find it.

11:36.463 --> 11:38.832
**

11:38.866 --> 11:40.167
Because I will be damned

11:40.200 --> 11:41.802
if I'm gonna have
my voice box removed

11:41.835 --> 11:43.136
just because
somebody screwed up.

11:43.170 --> 11:47.440
**

11:47.474 --> 11:50.343
I've implemented
a proactive educational plan.

11:50.377 --> 11:52.145
Well, that's terrific,
Shaun.

11:56.483 --> 11:59.019
Why are
we talking about that here?

11:59.052 --> 12:01.254
I'm not stupid.

12:01.288 --> 12:02.990
I didn't say
you were stupid, Shaun.

12:03.023 --> 12:04.291
Nobody said
you were stupid.

12:04.324 --> 12:05.793
But sometimes
you lack common sense.

12:05.826 --> 12:07.127
I'm so sorry
to have bothered you.

12:07.160 --> 12:10.197
This patient is deaf.

12:10.230 --> 12:11.765
Oh.

12:16.503 --> 12:19.940
I started flirting lessons
yesterday.

12:19.973 --> 12:21.408
Flirting lessons.

12:21.441 --> 12:23.376
Wish they'd had that
when I was young.

12:23.410 --> 12:27.047
Yes, I learned about
the flirting trifecta.

12:27.080 --> 12:28.381
There's
the pretentious giggle.

12:28.415 --> 12:30.217
Shaun,
what are you getting at?

12:30.250 --> 12:32.986
Flirting,

12:33.020 --> 12:36.356
it requires primarily
nonverbal interactions.

12:36.389 --> 12:38.959
Being perceptive
in one social dimension

12:38.992 --> 12:41.061
translates well
to other social skills.

12:41.094 --> 12:43.196
You're studying flirting.

12:43.230 --> 12:45.465
Are you lonely, Shaun?

12:45.498 --> 12:47.200
'Cause you know
there are --

12:47.234 --> 12:49.269
There are websites now
where you can --

12:49.302 --> 12:51.338
I like being alone.

12:51.371 --> 12:53.874
Yeah, well,
being alone and being lonely

12:53.907 --> 12:54.975
are two different things.

12:55.008 --> 12:57.978
Sometimes we're lonely,
and we don't even know it.

12:58.011 --> 13:01.548
How would I know it?

13:01.581 --> 13:04.918
Well, uh, loneliness,

13:04.952 --> 13:08.355
it's kind of a dull...

13:08.388 --> 13:09.456
It's like a dark...

13:09.489 --> 13:11.191
Are you lonely?

13:14.161 --> 13:17.164
Yeah, sometimes.

13:17.197 --> 13:19.566
You know,
sometimes very much.

13:23.336 --> 13:25.072
You should learn
the trifecta.

13:25.105 --> 13:32.212
**

13:32.245 --> 13:34.081
Hey. Um, hey.

13:34.114 --> 13:35.282
We're looking
for a lost specimen

13:35.315 --> 13:37.250
that I am positive
left the O.R.

13:37.284 --> 13:38.852
And I'm positive it didn't
make it to the lab.

13:38.886 --> 13:40.520
And since you're the link
between the two,

13:40.553 --> 13:43.023
we wanted to ask you
about your 3:00 run yesterday.

13:43.056 --> 13:44.357
So, you took everything

13:44.391 --> 13:46.359
that was in the refrigerator
in the O.R.?

13:46.393 --> 13:48.095
In the refrigerator,
out of the refrigerator.

13:48.128 --> 13:49.196
Everything that's meant to go,
I took.

13:49.229 --> 13:51.198
Did you stop on the way?
No.

13:51.231 --> 13:52.565
Straight from the surgery
to the lab,

13:52.599 --> 13:53.867
just like the rules say.

13:53.901 --> 13:55.568
Well, did you stop
at the restroom

13:55.602 --> 13:57.504
or the -- the coffee machine,
the cafeteria?

13:57.537 --> 13:59.372
You know, believe it or not,
I can go a whole 30 minutes

13:59.406 --> 14:01.041
without stopping
for a cream puff.

14:01.074 --> 14:02.275
We're just desperate.

14:02.309 --> 14:03.476
All we care about
is the specimen

14:03.510 --> 14:05.012
and avoiding
a full-on investigation.

14:05.045 --> 14:07.147
Investigation?

14:07.180 --> 14:10.083
Yeah.
Yeah, yeah.

14:10.117 --> 14:11.418
I-I-I-If we don't find it,

14:11.451 --> 14:13.320
then the legal department
gets involved.

14:13.353 --> 14:14.988
Everyone who was
in contact with it,

14:15.022 --> 14:16.556
who might have been
in contact with it

14:16.589 --> 14:18.091
goes under
a magnifying glass.

14:18.125 --> 14:19.259
I'm not looking forward
to it.

14:19.292 --> 14:21.561
You looking forward to it?
She's not looking forward to it.

14:21.594 --> 14:23.563
They're gonna check your
social media, your computer.

14:23.596 --> 14:26.166
Blood tests.
Blood tests.

14:26.199 --> 14:28.301
But if you find it
before then...?

14:28.335 --> 14:29.436
Then life goes on.

14:29.469 --> 14:31.038
The same
as it always has.

14:31.071 --> 14:33.941
I did stop.

14:33.974 --> 14:35.108
At the cafeteria.

14:35.142 --> 14:37.377
The cashier is smokin'.

14:37.410 --> 14:39.612
I might have been distracted
for a little while.

14:39.646 --> 14:42.015
Okay.

14:42.049 --> 14:43.383
Thanks.

14:45.018 --> 14:54.995
**

14:55.028 --> 15:04.237
**

15:04.271 --> 15:06.673
[ Toilet flushes ]

15:06.706 --> 15:11.444
**

15:11.478 --> 15:13.513
[ Toilet flushes ]

15:13.546 --> 15:14.681
**

15:14.714 --> 15:17.117
[ Toilet flushes ]

15:17.150 --> 15:26.326
**

15:26.359 --> 15:29.429
Water.

15:29.462 --> 15:31.498
Always more water.

15:31.531 --> 15:33.466
**

15:33.500 --> 15:34.734
Even more.

15:34.767 --> 15:37.704
**

15:37.737 --> 15:40.340
[ Sighs ]

15:40.373 --> 15:42.009
I know.
It's scary.

15:42.042 --> 15:46.513
**

15:46.546 --> 15:49.249
You are good with children.

15:49.282 --> 15:50.717
You are father?

15:50.750 --> 15:52.052
No.

15:52.085 --> 15:53.220
One day, I hope.

15:53.253 --> 15:56.990
[ Monitor beeping rapidly ]

15:57.024 --> 16:03.030
**

16:03.063 --> 16:13.040
**

16:13.073 --> 16:16.143
**

16:20.580 --> 16:22.182
The meds should've improved his
arrhythmia, not made it worse.

16:22.215 --> 16:23.483
Maybe in addition
to his other problems,

16:23.516 --> 16:24.517
he's developed
endocarditis.

16:24.551 --> 16:26.253
His echo
didn't reveal vegetations

16:26.286 --> 16:28.188
on his valves or...

16:28.221 --> 16:30.423
endocardium.

16:30.457 --> 16:32.525
He has not developed a fever.

16:32.559 --> 16:34.094
Let's be sure.
Get blood cultures.

16:34.127 --> 16:35.428
Order them times two,
15 minutes.

16:35.462 --> 16:36.496
It's in the wrong place.

16:36.529 --> 16:42.802
**

16:42.835 --> 16:44.737
It was in the wrong place.

16:44.771 --> 16:47.240
Okay.

16:47.274 --> 16:49.042
Times two.
15 minutes apart.

16:49.076 --> 16:58.518
**

16:58.551 --> 16:59.586
Hey.

16:59.619 --> 17:02.755
Um, Leonard says that
he stops by here to see you.

17:02.789 --> 17:04.624
[ Chuckles ]
Yeah.

17:04.657 --> 17:06.626
He pretends the cafeteria
is on his route.

17:06.659 --> 17:08.328
Like I don't know
where the lab is.

17:08.361 --> 17:09.829
Yesterday around 3:00,
Gwen.

17:09.862 --> 17:12.399
Notice anything on the food
trays that wasn't food?

17:12.432 --> 17:14.301
Around 3:00?
[ Blows ]

17:14.334 --> 17:15.835
Just the usual --

17:15.868 --> 17:20.707
uh, Tupperware, sunglasses,
cellphones, a condom.

17:20.740 --> 17:22.209
Around 4:00,
I found a glass eye.

17:22.242 --> 17:23.743
You see a biohazard bag?

17:23.776 --> 17:27.080
Uh, the ziplock bag
with the red circles?

17:27.114 --> 17:29.316
Yeah.

17:29.349 --> 17:31.184
C'mon.

17:31.218 --> 17:34.554
**

17:34.587 --> 17:37.290
You can move
the mitral valve.

17:37.324 --> 17:38.858
Thanks
for the visual aid.

17:38.891 --> 17:40.860
You can't move
the mitral valve.

17:40.893 --> 17:43.430
Now, if Mr. Potato Head
had an atrial septal nose

17:43.463 --> 17:44.697
and hypertrophic
obstructive --
I believe --

17:44.731 --> 17:46.866
I believe
the abnormal insertion

17:46.899 --> 17:48.701
of the mitral valve
can be --
Stop.

17:48.735 --> 17:51.238
**

17:51.271 --> 17:54.774
Follow me.

17:54.807 --> 17:58.611
Pretty sure I saw a biohazard
bag in here yesterday.

17:58.645 --> 18:00.347
You're lucky
you came when you did.

18:00.380 --> 18:02.749
It's due to get dumped
in two hours.

18:02.782 --> 18:05.818
Ugh, dentures.
They're the worst.

18:05.852 --> 18:07.354
You know, every patient
gets a denture cup

18:07.387 --> 18:08.855
with their name on it.

18:08.888 --> 18:11.191
So, tell me, why are
the dentures never in the cup?

18:11.224 --> 18:12.892
And if they are,
it's the wrong cup?

18:12.925 --> 18:15.428
One of life's mysteries.

18:15.462 --> 18:18.765
Biohazard bag sighting.

18:18.798 --> 18:20.600
A biohazard bag
for a coin purse?

18:20.633 --> 18:21.601
Really?

18:21.634 --> 18:23.803
[ Sighs ]

18:23.836 --> 18:26.439
Finally,
a septal myectomy

18:26.473 --> 18:27.874
will open
the outflow tract,

18:27.907 --> 18:29.542
and the mitral valve
can be re-implanted

18:29.576 --> 18:31.611
into
a more normal position.

18:31.644 --> 18:33.646
Thank you.
That's my idea.

18:33.680 --> 18:35.615
Can you do this procedure
on Gabriel?

18:35.648 --> 18:38.185
No.

18:38.218 --> 18:40.187
It's a terrible idea,
and it won't work.

18:40.220 --> 18:41.921
So, what was the point
of this dog and pony show?

18:41.954 --> 18:44.557
'Cause you seemed keen on
making medical decisions for me.

18:44.591 --> 18:46.359
So just insubordination?

18:46.393 --> 18:49.229
And we were probably gonna
wind up coming to you anyway.

18:49.262 --> 18:51.331
Once Dr. Murphy gets an idea,
he stays with it,

18:51.364 --> 18:52.699
regardless
of what anyone says.

18:52.732 --> 18:54.601
This can work.

18:54.634 --> 18:56.936
Yes, this can work.

18:56.969 --> 19:00.240
And it would be a great idea if
the boy had two hours to live.

19:00.273 --> 19:03.443
Is fear of failure
a good reason not to do this?

19:05.612 --> 19:07.680
No.

19:07.714 --> 19:09.816
But you know what is?

19:09.849 --> 19:12.819
The thought that he might have
a few more birthdays...

19:12.852 --> 19:14.821
or make a best friend.

19:14.854 --> 19:16.789
And...I don't know.

19:16.823 --> 19:19.326
I'm not sending him home
in a box.

19:19.359 --> 19:21.494
[ Cellphone vibrates ]

19:21.528 --> 19:23.396
We got to go.

19:23.430 --> 19:24.831
Gabriel's arrhythmia,
it's gotten worse.

19:26.366 --> 19:27.834
Elizabeth:
You still haven't found it?

19:27.867 --> 19:30.270
I can get Ms. Preston
to address any questions --

19:30.303 --> 19:32.205
She wasn't in the surgery.
You were.

19:32.239 --> 19:35.208
She is the point person for
all therapeutic misadventures.

19:35.242 --> 19:37.210
Are you kidding me?

19:37.244 --> 19:40.847
I may lose my voice
for absolutely no reason,

19:40.880 --> 19:42.649
and you are using
canned jargon.

19:42.682 --> 19:45.252
That sample cup
doesn't have toothpaste

19:45.285 --> 19:47.287
or socks or sunblock in it,
okay?

19:47.320 --> 19:48.721
It has my life!

19:48.755 --> 19:53.293
**

19:53.326 --> 19:54.927
I'm sorry.

19:57.364 --> 19:58.731
Thank you.

19:58.765 --> 20:00.767
[ Sighs ]

20:04.904 --> 20:07.674
Good for you.
Yeah, right.

20:07.707 --> 20:10.277
I just broke
about eight rules.
Maybe.

20:10.310 --> 20:11.744
"Ms. Preston" won't hear
about it from me.

20:11.778 --> 20:13.880
[ Chuckles ]

20:13.913 --> 20:15.682
You should go find
that sample, though.

20:15.715 --> 20:17.384
**

20:17.417 --> 20:18.751
Thanks.

20:18.785 --> 20:21.921
**

20:21.954 --> 20:25.925
The meds aren't working.
The question is why.

20:25.958 --> 20:29.796
M-Maybe the arrhythmia
is just another manifestation

20:29.829 --> 20:31.364
of Gabriel's
L.V. dysfunction.

20:31.398 --> 20:33.666
We should still be seeing
at least a modest decline

20:33.700 --> 20:36.269
in his ectopy.
Maybe his gradient is worse.

20:36.303 --> 20:37.837
We could try
calcium channel blockers.

20:37.870 --> 20:40.373
There's
a much simpler explanation.

20:40.407 --> 20:47.614
**

20:47.647 --> 20:49.949
Melendez: Good news
about his endocarditis --

20:49.982 --> 20:50.983
heart inflammation.

20:51.017 --> 20:52.919
His tests are normal.

20:52.952 --> 20:55.288
But we still are concerned.

20:55.322 --> 20:58.625
For some reason,
his medication isn't helping.

20:58.658 --> 21:00.860
Our best explanation is...

21:00.893 --> 21:02.995
he hasn't been taking
his medication.

21:17.777 --> 21:19.779
I am trying
to save his life.

21:19.812 --> 21:20.880
But withholding
his medicine?

21:20.913 --> 21:23.583
By keeping him here.

21:23.616 --> 21:25.452
If he takes the medicine
and becomes better,

21:25.485 --> 21:27.320
you send him to die.

21:27.354 --> 21:29.756
But there is nothing else
that we can do for him here.

21:29.789 --> 21:34.527
You do not understand
where I live, what it is like.

21:34.561 --> 21:37.597
I don't know your village.

21:37.630 --> 21:39.632
But I do know
what it's like to be poor.

21:41.534 --> 21:43.470
I grew up with nothing.

21:43.503 --> 21:44.504
My sister was disabled.

21:44.537 --> 21:47.440
My parents couldn't afford
her meds or treatments.

21:47.474 --> 21:51.678
And it killed them, and me,
to watch her suffer.

21:51.711 --> 21:56.716
But when nothing can be done,
nothing can be done.

21:56.749 --> 21:59.419
You became a doctor?

22:01.120 --> 22:03.756
You did not accept
being poor.

22:03.790 --> 22:06.459
No.

22:06.493 --> 22:09.996
Then you do not understand
at all.

22:12.932 --> 22:15.902
We want for everything --
food.

22:15.935 --> 22:19.939
Peace. Medicine.

22:19.972 --> 22:24.644
But our greatest want
is hope.

22:24.677 --> 22:27.547
**

22:27.580 --> 22:30.116
If we leave here,
we leave hope behind.

22:30.149 --> 22:38.525
**

22:38.558 --> 22:39.792
Okay.

22:39.826 --> 22:42.695
I'll do what I can.

22:47.867 --> 22:48.701
I dropped by
to see Elizabeth.

22:48.735 --> 22:49.869
Not surprisingly,
she's very upset.

22:49.902 --> 22:52.071
There wasn't much I could offer
in the way of comfort.

22:52.104 --> 22:53.406
If only people
did their jobs.

22:53.440 --> 22:54.674
Which people?

22:54.707 --> 22:58.745
Scrub nurses,
couriers, lab techs...

22:58.778 --> 23:00.613
That's
a curiously limited list.

23:00.647 --> 23:01.948
I did the surgery correctly.

23:01.981 --> 23:03.416
I don't think it's too much
to expect others

23:03.450 --> 23:05.452
to do their jobs correctly,
as well.

23:05.485 --> 23:07.420
So, not your fault,
not your problem.

23:07.454 --> 23:08.921
What are you trying to do,
make me feel guilty?

23:08.955 --> 23:11.057
Yes.
I want you to feel horrible.

23:11.090 --> 23:12.792
That's the only thing
that's gonna make you change.

23:12.825 --> 23:14.794
Into what?
The guy I married.

23:14.827 --> 23:17.564
The guy who cared more
about patients than politics.

23:17.597 --> 23:19.566
Ah, okay, I get it.

23:19.599 --> 23:22.034
This is about me vying
for president of the hospital.

23:22.068 --> 23:23.803
Which we discussed
at length,

23:23.836 --> 23:26.639
which you said you were
100% behind me on.

23:26.673 --> 23:28.007
I didn't realize
how far behind.

23:28.040 --> 23:29.776
You think
I've left you behind?

23:29.809 --> 23:31.511
Hmm.

23:31.544 --> 23:34.447
Uh, Tuesday --

23:34.481 --> 23:36.015
"Capital expenditures meeting
delayed.

23:36.048 --> 23:37.216
Will be late."

23:37.249 --> 23:38.918
Wednesday --
"Fundraising event ran over.

23:38.951 --> 23:40.653
Don't wait up."

23:40.687 --> 23:42.154
Thursday --
Iz, there are things
about my job --

23:42.188 --> 23:43.656
Right.

23:43.690 --> 23:45.124
"Not your fault."

23:48.060 --> 23:57.737
**

23:57.770 --> 23:58.571
Shaun: Hello.

23:58.605 --> 24:01.007
Hey.

24:01.040 --> 24:04.243
Did you know that specimens
in formalin go to one place,

24:04.276 --> 24:06.145
exempt specimens
somewhere else,

24:06.178 --> 24:07.814
aerobic
and anaerobic cultures --

24:07.847 --> 24:09.048
two different places?

24:09.081 --> 24:11.183
Um, radioactive,
medical device,

24:11.217 --> 24:13.553
forensic specimens --
all different?

24:13.586 --> 24:14.754
And all handled
by different staff?

24:14.787 --> 24:15.555
Did you know that?

24:15.588 --> 24:18.024
Yes.

24:18.057 --> 24:19.125
Oh.

24:19.158 --> 24:21.561
I made a chart, too.

24:21.594 --> 24:23.963
A qualitative observation log
of what you taught me.

24:23.996 --> 24:24.964
What did I teach you?

24:24.997 --> 24:26.799
Flirting.

24:26.833 --> 24:29.168
Every time I saw
someone flirt, I noted it

24:29.201 --> 24:30.737
and cross-referenced
the subject,

24:30.770 --> 24:33.139
object,
and nonverbal gestures.

24:33.172 --> 24:34.774
[ Chuckles ]
I knew it.

24:34.807 --> 24:36.676
Gwen, the cashier.

24:36.709 --> 24:39.245
She made out that it was
all the courier, but --

24:39.278 --> 24:40.647
That's my name.

24:40.680 --> 24:42.081
Yes.
You made flirting gestures.

24:42.114 --> 24:43.683
No, I didn't.
Yes, you did.

24:43.716 --> 24:46.152
You brushed your hair back.

24:46.185 --> 24:49.822
Right hand,
side sweeping.

24:49.856 --> 24:53.025
At Dr. Melendez?

24:53.059 --> 24:55.962
No, I don't think so.
Shaun.

24:55.995 --> 24:57.564
No.
Yes.

24:57.597 --> 24:59.198
You were
at the nurses station,

24:59.231 --> 25:01.200
and he said,
"Good for you,"

25:01.233 --> 25:03.870
and you said, "Yeah, right.
I just broke about eight rules,"

25:03.903 --> 25:05.805
and smiled and giggled
and brushed your hair back.

25:05.838 --> 25:08.675
**

25:08.708 --> 25:10.276
"Ms. Preston" won't hear
about it from me.

25:10.309 --> 25:13.112
[ Chuckles ]

25:13.145 --> 25:15.648
**

25:15.682 --> 25:17.516
It's possible
you have ringworm.

25:19.619 --> 25:22.088
Shaun, sometimes people
toss their hair

25:22.121 --> 25:23.590
just 'cause
it's in their face.

25:23.623 --> 25:25.291
Melendez: Murphy.

25:25.324 --> 25:26.859
I'd like you to elaborate
on your idea.

25:26.893 --> 25:28.695
Mm, my terrible idea?

25:28.728 --> 25:29.762
That's the one.

25:29.796 --> 25:31.964
[ Chuckles ]

25:31.998 --> 25:42.008
**

25:42.041 --> 25:43.576
**

25:43.610 --> 25:46.078
You can move the anterior
leaflet of the valve

25:46.112 --> 25:46.979
and reattach it.

25:47.013 --> 25:50.049
No, we can't.

25:50.082 --> 25:52.852
This is an exact replica
of the kid's heart,

25:52.885 --> 25:55.788
and there's no anchor point
to reattach it.

25:55.822 --> 25:57.256
So that part of your idea
is still terrible.

25:57.289 --> 26:00.126
Okay.

26:00.159 --> 26:01.594
But the rest of it?

26:01.628 --> 26:03.229
We're dealing
with a huge septum --

26:03.262 --> 26:04.831
25 millimeters.

26:04.864 --> 26:06.132
What would that number be
in a healthy kid?

26:06.165 --> 26:07.700
About 8.

26:07.734 --> 26:09.335
If we go
anywhere near that number,

26:09.368 --> 26:12.104
we won't have enough support
for the valve.

26:14.273 --> 26:18.377
But let's say
we took that down to 20...

26:18.410 --> 26:19.879
[ Chuckles ]
That won't be enough

26:19.912 --> 26:22.081
to relieve
the outflow obstruction.

26:25.017 --> 26:26.919
Okay.

26:26.953 --> 26:28.587
18.

26:29.956 --> 26:31.624
Okay.

26:31.658 --> 26:41.668
**

26:41.701 --> 26:51.678
**

26:51.711 --> 27:01.688
**

27:01.721 --> 27:11.764
**

27:11.798 --> 27:21.774
**

27:21.808 --> 27:25.311
**

27:25.344 --> 27:26.378
Let's take him off bypass.

27:26.412 --> 27:34.120
**

27:34.153 --> 27:36.222
[ Flatline ]

27:36.255 --> 27:38.991
**

27:39.025 --> 27:39.959
He's dead.

27:39.992 --> 27:42.428
Again. 16.

27:42.461 --> 27:44.864
Claire:
I'm really tired.

27:44.897 --> 27:49.268
I used to think
that I wanted to be

27:49.301 --> 27:51.137
the best surgeon
in history.

27:51.170 --> 27:53.039
But my new goal?

27:53.072 --> 27:56.743
Is just not to get washed out
of my residency.

27:56.776 --> 27:58.845
[ Footsteps approaching ]

27:58.878 --> 28:01.714
Claire:
You have a surgery now?

28:01.748 --> 28:02.815
No.

28:02.849 --> 28:04.784
I'm here to see
how I can help.

28:04.817 --> 28:07.186
The Chief of Surgery
joining the search party?

28:07.219 --> 28:08.755
Should I take a selfie,

28:08.788 --> 28:10.122
show my friends that
this really happened?

28:10.156 --> 28:11.824
This is a team problem.

28:11.858 --> 28:13.425
It should be
a team solution.

28:13.459 --> 28:15.762
How do you get
a boss like this?

28:15.795 --> 28:17.496
What do we know so far?

28:17.529 --> 28:23.269
**

28:23.302 --> 28:24.837
Let's take him off bypass.

28:24.871 --> 28:27.206
**

28:27.239 --> 28:29.108
[ Monitor beeping ]

28:29.141 --> 28:33.279
**

28:33.312 --> 28:36.015
[ Monitor beeping ]

28:36.048 --> 28:39.385
His outflow is perfect
at 13 millimeters.

28:39.418 --> 28:42.321
Which is irrelevant
when the mitral valve...
[ Flatline ]

28:42.354 --> 28:44.423
...doesn't have
enough support to close.

28:44.456 --> 28:48.060
He's dead.

28:48.094 --> 28:49.495
Again.

28:49.528 --> 28:51.163
**

28:51.197 --> 28:52.765
Jessica: Dr. Browne.

28:52.799 --> 28:54.801
Any reason
you assumed responsibility

28:54.834 --> 28:56.769
on behalf
of the hospital...

28:56.803 --> 29:00.172
told Elizabeth
you were "sorry"?

29:00.206 --> 29:02.108
Because I was.

29:06.078 --> 29:08.480
Well, I hope we don't see
the price tag on that.

29:10.950 --> 29:13.185
And I think
you're out of time.

29:13.219 --> 29:21.360
**

29:21.393 --> 29:23.262
Let's take him off bypass.

29:23.295 --> 29:27.366
**

29:27.399 --> 29:29.101
[ Monitor beeping ]

29:29.135 --> 29:34.907
**

29:34.941 --> 29:36.375
Yes.

29:38.310 --> 29:40.312
14 millimeters.

29:40.346 --> 29:42.815
Exactly.

29:42.849 --> 29:44.283
Yeah.

29:44.316 --> 29:46.986
Exactly.

29:47.019 --> 29:51.490
Our margin of error
is exceedingly low.

29:51.523 --> 29:54.126
Good luck.

29:54.160 --> 29:56.228
You believe in luck?

29:56.262 --> 29:59.798
It's something people say
in difficult situations.

30:02.902 --> 30:04.103
Neither do I.

30:04.136 --> 30:05.137
Again.

30:05.171 --> 30:07.239
**

30:07.273 --> 30:10.309
Isabel: The reality is, even
if we found your specimen now,

30:10.342 --> 30:13.980
it's unlikely
that it'd still be viable.

30:16.916 --> 30:20.920
You don't know
if I have cancer,

30:20.953 --> 30:22.321
and there's no way
to find out.

30:24.356 --> 30:29.328
So my choices
are surgery I may not need...

30:31.330 --> 30:34.934
...that will leave me
without speech,

30:34.967 --> 30:37.369
or I do nothing
and maybe die.

30:37.403 --> 30:40.940
Unfortunately, yes.

30:40.973 --> 30:48.948
**

30:48.981 --> 30:52.952
* Oh

30:52.985 --> 30:57.389
* That ancient light, weigh

30:57.423 --> 30:58.991
* Mm-mm-mm

30:59.025 --> 31:00.559
* Mm-mm-mm-mm-mm

31:00.592 --> 31:05.631
* On your shoulders

31:05.664 --> 31:09.936
* And the river of time

31:09.969 --> 31:17.176
* Love is all that's left
to lose *

31:17.209 --> 31:21.647
* Love is all that's left
to lose *

31:23.682 --> 31:27.253
* Oh-oh-oh, oh-oh-oh

31:27.286 --> 31:30.957
* Oh-oh-oh-oh, oh-oh

31:30.990 --> 31:34.193
* Oh-oh-oh, oh-oh-oh

31:34.226 --> 31:37.629
* Oh-oh-oh-oh, oh-oh

31:37.663 --> 31:41.633
* Lust, love

31:41.667 --> 31:44.603
* I'm not alone anymore

31:44.636 --> 31:48.707
* Lust, love

31:48.740 --> 31:53.512
* I'm not alone anymore

